> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Pattee","meanings":["Altered form of French (Nord) <b>Pety</b>: variant of   Petit  . This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Petion","meanings":["French and Haitian (<b>Pétion</b>): diminutive of   Petit  . This surname was brought to the US from Haiti, where it is by far most common."]},{"name":"Petite","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Celestine, Jacques.","French: from the feminine form of   Petit   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Petitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettett","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Little","meanings":["English: nickname for a small man (if not ironic), or distinguishing epithet for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, from Middle English <i>littel</i>, Old English <i>lȳtel</i> (see   Light   3).","Irish: translation into English of Gaelic <b>Ó Beagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beagán</i>’ (see   Began  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of any of various European surnames meaning ‘little’, e.g. French   Petit  , Polish <b>Mały</b> (see   Maly   1)."]},{"name":"Petee","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettit","meanings":["English (mainly southeastern): variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Petito","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Pasquale, Antonio, Rocco, Alfonzo, Alphonso, Antimo, Emilio, Giovanni, Giuseppe, Orazio, Salvatore, Silvio, Tullio, Virginio.","Italian: nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a tall one), from dialect <i>petito</i> ‘small’ or from the personal name <i>Petito</i>; compare French   Petit  ."]}]},{"name":"Aluric","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Germanic personal name composed of <i>ala</i> ‘all’ or <i>ali</i> ‘stranger’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. Now rare, it was introduced to Britain in this form by the Normans. The first element may also in part derive from a contracted form of <i>adal</i> ‘noble’. The Blessed Alaricus or Adalricus (  d. 975 ) was a Swabian prince who became a monk at the monastery of Einsiedeln in Switzerland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Aluric Petit was born in 1110, in Philleigh, Cornwall, England. He had at least 1 son with Mathilda Le Boteler de Camerton. He died in 1180, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1110–1180":"1110–1180","1115–1195":"1115–1195","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1115":"1115","1200":"1200","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1180":"1180","Ardevora-Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1110–1180":"1110–1180","1115–1195":"1115–1195","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1115":"1115","1200":"1200","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1180":"1180","Ardevora-Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England"},"fr":{"1110–1180":"1110–1180","1115–1195":"1115–1195","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1115":"1115","1200":"1200","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1180":"1180","Ardevora-Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornouailles, Angleterre","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornouailles, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Aluric Petit est né en 1110, à Philleigh, Cornouailles, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mathilda Le B